# Linux Password Reset Steps (Offline Method using Live CD)

# 0. Boot from a Linux Live CD (e.g., Ubuntu, Debian, etc.)
#    - Insert the bootable USB/DVD.
#    - Reboot the system and enter the BIOS/UEFI menu (usually by pressing F2, F10, F12, DEL or ESC).
#    - Select the USB/DVD to boot into Live Linux.

# Optional: Press Ctrl+Shift+F1 to switch to a TTY terminal from GUI live session (if needed).

# Once you're in a terminal:

# 1. List block devices to identify your root disk
lsblk

# Example output helps you find where root partition (e.g., /dev/sda2 or /dev/mapper/pve-root) is.

# 2. Create a mount point
mkdir /mnt/reset

# 3. Activate all volume groups (needed for LVM-based systems like Proxmox)
vgchange -ay

# 4. Scan and identify logical volumes (verify the correct path)
lvscan

# 5. Mount the root logical volume (adjust if your system is not using LVM)
mount /dev/mapper/pve-root /mnt/reset

# 6. Change root into the mounted system
chroot /mnt/reset

# 7. Reset the password for the user (replace dbuadmin with your username if needed)
passwd dbuadmin
# Enter new password when prompted

# 8. Exit chroot environment
exit

# 9. Unmount the system
umount /mnt/reset

# 10. Reboot the system
reboot
